






#lg 25.1	proverb

@(25.1.1 = 1-4)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.03,t.6.1.03.149]{6.1.03.149}, @xref[t.6.1.14,t.6.1.14.6]{6.1.14.6}, @xref[t.6.1.15,t.6.1.15.b5]{6.1.15.b5}, @xref[t.6.1.16,t.6.1.16.c5]{6.1.16.c5}, @xref[t.6.1.22,]{6.1.22: ll. 172-175}} It became cloudy, but it did not rain. It rained, but no one undid their belt. Although the @wWN{Tigris} was on its high tide, no water reached the arable lands. It rained on the riverbank, but the dry land did not get any of it.

#lg 25.2	proverb

@(25.2.5 = 5-6)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.15,t.6.1.15.b7]{6.1.15.b7}} The @fsux{en} priest eats fish and eats leeks; but cress makes him ill.

#lg 25.3	proverb

@(25.3.7 = 7-8)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.03,t.6.1.03.59]{6.1.03.59}} The lord @note{i.e. @wDN{An} (?)} cursed @wSN{Unug}, but he himself was cursed by the lady of @wTN{E-ana} @note{i.e. @wDN{Inana}}.

#lg 25.4	proverb

@(25.4.9 = 9-15)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.03,t.6.1.03.31]{6.1.03.31}, @xref[t.6.1.09,t.6.1.09.b1]{6.1.09.b1}, @xref[t.6.1.11,t.6.1.11.18]{6.1.11.18}, @xref[t.6.1.15,t.6.1.15.b8]{6.1.15.b8}, @xref[t.6.2.1,]{6.2.1: Ni 4469 Seg. A ll. 9-12}} @wRN{Nanni} cherished his old age. He had not finished the building of @wDN{Enlil's} temple. He …… the building of the wall of @wSN{Nibru}. He had abandoned the building of the @wTN{E-ana}, ……. He had captured @wSN{Simurrum}, but had not managed to carry off (?) its tribute. Mighty kingship was not bestowed upon him. Was not @wRN{Nanni} thus brought to the nether world with a depressed heart?

#lg 25.5	proverb

@(25.5.16 = 16-20)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.01,t.6.1.01.57]{6.1.01.57}} Although the number of unhappy days is endless (?), yet life is better than death ……. When I ……  ((2 lines fragmentary)) 

#lg 25.6	proverb

@(25.6.21 = 21-22)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.01,t.6.1.01.68]{6.1.01.68}, @xref[t.6.1.14,t.6.1.14.15]{6.1.14.15}} Into a plague-stricken city one has to be driven like a pack-ass.

#lg 25.7	proverb

@(25.7.23 = 23-24)  @note{= Alster 1997 25.8; cf. @xref[t.6.1.02,t.6.1.02.142]{6.1.02.142}, @xref[t.6.1.23,t.6.1.23.7]{6.1.23.7}} A house built by a righteous man is destroyed by a treacherous man.

#lg 25.8	proverb

@(25.8.25 = 25-26)  @note{= Alster 1997 25.7; cf. @xref[t.6.1.02,t.6.1.02.156]{6.1.02.156}, @xref[t.6.1.02,t.6.1.02.161]{6.1.02.161}, @xref[t.6.1.03,t.6.1.03.165]{6.1.03.165}, @xref[t.6.1.14,t.6.1.14.23]{6.1.14.23}} The palace is a slippery place, where one slips. Watch your step when you decide to go home!

#lg 25.9	proverb

@(25.9.27 = 27)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.11,t.6.1.11.56]{6.1.11.56}, @xref[t.6.1.26,t.6.1.26.a2]{6.1.26.a2}, @xref[t.6.2.5,]{6.2.5: UM 29-16-519 Seg. B l. 2}} The palace bows down, but only of its own accord.

#lg 25.10	proverb

@(25.10.28 = 28)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.02,t.6.1.02.158]{6.1.02.158}, @xref[t.6.1.14,t.6.1.14.22]{6.1.14.22}, @xref[t.6.1.17,t.6.1.17.b9]{6.1.17.b9}} The palace -- one day a lamenting mother, the next day a mother giving birth.

#lg 25.11	proverb

@(25.11.29 = 29-30)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.02,t.6.1.02.157]{6.1.02.157}, @xref[t.6.1.14,t.6.1.14.20]{6.1.14.20}, @xref[t.6.2.3,t623.h27]{6.2.3: UET 6/2 317}} Even the palace cannot avoid the wasteland. Even a barge cannot avoid straw. Even a nobleman cannot avoid corvée work.

#lg 25.12	proverb

@(25.12.31 = 31-34)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.26,t.6.1.26.a3]{6.1.26.a3}, @xref[t.6.2.5,t625.h28]{6.2.5: YBC 9908}, @xref[t.5.6.1,]{5.6.1: ll. 95-96}} What flows in is never enough to fill it, and what flows out can never be stopped -- don't envy the king's property!

#lg 25.13	proverb

@(25.13.35 = 35-36)  @note{cf. @xref[t.6.1.03,t.6.1.03.170]{6.1.03.170}, @xref[t.6.1.26,t.6.1.26.a10]{6.1.26.a10}, @xref[t.6.2.5,]{6.2.5: BM 57994 Seg. A ll. 1-3}} When a man sailing downstream encounters a man whose boat is travelling upstream, an inspection is an abomination to @wDN{Suen}.



